snippet.textDisplay: My personal observation of the fight: Usman was the more technical striker with an edge in the power department. Colby had more output, but it was a more brawling style. I had it tied a two rounds a piece going into the fifth. What amazed me was that, even with a broken jaw, Colby won the fourth and was winning the fifth until he got caught. It makes me wonder what would the outcome would have been if he didn't have a broken jaw. I'd love to see a rematch after Kamaru faces someone else and Colby gets back on track with a win over another ranked opponent - preferably Woodley.

How can anyone complain with the stoppage? He had been dropped twice in that round.

snippet.textDisplay:
Watched the slo-mo. If eye strike happened, it w/h been pinky, 5th finger of Covington. It didn't look intentional. Low kick was barely low and did not appear to contact the groin. Looked like Usman tried to play it up. Covington's head was low and neck bent @ end of 5, so I'm on the fence w. regard to stoppage. The slow-mo of Usman right to Covington jaw did look very powerful and capable of breaking the jaw. We now know it did. I think Usman was ahead going into Rd 5, on points, but not by much. I think Usman won, but not by much, and not until the last part of Rd 5, when Covington appeared tired after getting knocked down by Usman's punch.
If it turns out Usman was in EPO at any time in the last year, his win was a fraud and should be stripped from him. Likewise for Covington.

snippet.textDisplay: The one detail that separated the two in the fight, was Usman's body shots (front kick and punches). It started to suck the life out of Colby from the start, which cost him some of one of his greatest assets, which is his steady pace and stamina. Brilliant on Usman's part. In a rematch Colby would be smart to employ the same strategy back at Usman. Colby's rear power hand would hit Usman's liver side. Colby's left kick was blocked, as Usman had that angle covered with his guard, so Colby would need to employ a rear leg front kick, or a stabbing type kick to the body like a Semmy Schilt used to use. As well, he would benefit  from the step in knee but to the body rather than the head as I think he was doing. Usman in a rematch would simply have to do the same. Then it becomes a question as to who has the counter to the body attack, hard wired in, for fight time.
